<p><i><b>Salem's Lot</b></i> (also known as <i><b>Salem's Lot: The Movie</b></i>, <i><b>Salem's Lot: The Miniseries</b></i> and <i><b>Blood Thirst</b></i>) is a 1979 <a href="/wiki/Cinema_of_the_United_States" title="Cinema of the United States">American</a> <a href="/wiki/Television_adaptation" title="Television adaptation" class="mw-redirect">television adaptation</a> of the <a href="/wiki/%27Salem%27s_Lot" title="'Salem's Lot">novel of the same name</a> by <a href="/wiki/Stephen_King" title="Stephen King">Stephen King</a>. Directed by <a href="/wiki/Tobe_Hooper" title="Tobe Hooper">Tobe Hooper</a> and starring <a href="/wiki/David_Soul" title="David Soul">David Soul</a> and <a href="/wiki/James_Mason" title="James Mason">James Mason</a>, the plot revolves around a writer returning to his home town and discovers the citizens are turning into <a href="/wiki/Vampires" title="Vampires" class="mw-redirect">vampires</a>. It combines elements of both the <a href="/wiki/Vampire_film" title="Vampire film">vampire film</a> and <a href="/wiki/Haunted_house" title="Haunted house">haunted house</a> subgenres.</p>
<p></p>
